					<div class="section-row">
						<h3>What types of bonds are there?</h3>
						<figure>
							<img src="./img/verne-ho-0lajfsna-xq-unsplash.jpg" alt="">
						</figure>
						 <strong>What types of bonds are there?</strong><p><span></span></p><figure><div><div></div><div><img></div><div></div></div><meta><figcaption><span>Types of bonds " Investor's Diary"</span></figcaption></figure><h3><span>In this article, we will analyze such a popular exchange-traded instrument as bonds. This tool is very often used by professional market participants, and individuals due to the fact that they are not able to because of their ignorance and fear, they prefer to use Bank deposits. </span></h3><p><span>In fact, everyone can use this tool without extra knowledge. Some people have already started to get acquainted with them through banks by buying people's OFZs.</span></p><p><span>Let's analyze the main types of bonds and how you can buy them in two clicks and get a greater return than in a Bank sometimes 2-3 times more at the same risks as in a Bank.</span></p><blockquote><span><b>Depending on the sector:</b></span></blockquote><ul><li><span>Public (OFZ), the most reliable, coupon every six months</span></li><li><span>Municipalities (region, region, city) how to melt, amortize with a coupon once a month quarter</span></li><li><span>Corporate, the largest selection</span></li></ul><blockquote><span><b>By maturity date:</b></span></blockquote><ul><li><span>Short-term (up to 2 years)</span></li><li><span>Medium-term ( from 3 to 5 years)</span></li><li><span>Long-term ( from 5 years)</span></li></ul><blockquote><span><b>Depending on the revenue generation method:</b></span></blockquote><ul><li><span>Bonds with fixed permanent coupon</span></li><li><span>Fixed variable coupon bonds</span></li><li><span>Bonds with floating coupon</span></li><li><span>Indexed bonds</span></li></ul><blockquote><span><b>Depending on the method of payment of coupon:</b></span></blockquote><ul><li><span>Interest-bearing bonds </span></li><li><span>-</span><span><i>Coupon bond</i></span><span> (bonds with periodic coupon payments)</span></li><li><span>-</span><span><i>Cumulative coupon bonds </i></span><span>( when redeemed, the investor receives the nominal value of the bond and the total coupon income)</span></li><li><span>Coupon-free bonds (zero-coupon bonds). When issuing coupon-free bonds, the yield on them is calculated as follows: it is paid, as a rule, in the form of the difference between the nominal value of the bond and its placement price.</span></li></ul><blockquote><span><b>According to the method of repayment of the nominal value:</b></span></blockquote><ul><li><span>Bonds with par value redeemable by a one-time payment at the end of the term.</span></li><li><span>Bonds with a maturity distribution of time (depreciation)</span></li></ul><blockquote><span><b>Depending on the possibility of early repayment of the bond:</b></span></blockquote><ul><li><span>Non-early redemption bonds</span></li><li><span>Bonds with a built-in call option ( according to these bonds, the Issuer has the right to fully or partially repay the debt before the set date redemptions)</span></li><li><span>Bonds with a built-in put option ( according to these bonds, the investor has the right to repay the debt on the set date)</span></li></ul><p><span>This may seem very difficult at first, but start a little at a time with the simplest ones. </span><span><b>For a novice investor, you should start only with short-term OFZs with with a fixed coupon and indexed ones, such as OFZ 29011.</b></span></p><p><span>In order to buy bonds, you need to open an account with any broker, make money to a brokerage account and buy them through the program or your personal account.</span></p><p><span>You can read about the main concepts in the bond market</span><span><b> </b></span><span></span><a><b>here.</b></a></p><h2><span><b>Subscribe to the channel and put likes!</b></span><span></span><a><b> </b></a></h2><div></div>
